+- unfair budget, metrics, seeds, uncertainty, resource, or stopping criteria;
+- missing single-module or leave-one-out ablation;
+- weak module-composition novelty;
+- unsupported observed result;
+- missing paper-to-method attribution;
+- non-finite metrics and duplicate identifiers.
+
+### Acceptance
+
+- Blocking provenance, license, compute, or semantic failures cannot return `GO`.
+- Composition-only novelty returns at most `REVISE`.
+- Every borrowed component maps to a source, role, interface, adapter, predicted effect, and failure mode.
+- Baseline, full, single-module, and required leave-one-out arms use a fair comparison signature.
+
+## 12. Gate I — academic-tailoring evidence scope and Agent evaluation
+
+### Procedure
+
+```bash
+python scripts/run_academic_tailoring_eval.py \
+  --output-dir build/academic-tailoring-eval
+```
+
+Run the plugin `propose` operation on the committed NPC fixture and inspect both output and evidence metadata.
+
+### Acceptance
+
+- All committed synthetic cases match expected decisions and quality thresholds.
+- Every expected target remains `proposed` unless an immutable evidence ID is present.
+- Synthetic fixtures report:
+  - `evidence_scope=synthetic_evaluation`;
+  - `readiness=synthetic_evaluation_only`;
+  - `scientific_release_ready=false`.
+- Verified real source cards can report `ready_for_controlled_experiment`, but still report `scientific_release_ready=false` before experiments and expert review.
+- Corpus artifacts and digests are reproducible.
+- The report explicitly states that the corpus evaluates contract handling, not real scientific validity or global novelty.
+
+## 13. Gate J — web, browser, container, and local deployment
+
+### Procedure
+
+- Serve the installed package on loopback.
+- Run headless Chromium submit → progress → review → export.
+- Build the Docker image.
+- Run as the configured unprivileged user with a persistent `/data` volume.
+- Confirm `/readyz` and packaged assets.
+- Attempt non-loopback bind without acknowledgement and confirm refusal.
+
+### Acceptance
+
+- Browser contains no provider key or Agent decision logic.
+- CSP and package-local assets remain intact.
+- Public binding requires explicit acknowledgement and is still documented as unauthenticated/trusted-network only.
+- Container restart preserves terminal state and fails in-flight work closed.
+
+## 14. Gate K — live provider engineering acceptance
+
+This gate requires repository secrets and must be opt-in.
+
+### Procedure
+
+1. Store `MISTRAL_API_KEY` only in GitHub repository Secrets.
+2. Validate all four production structured schemas with the configured real model.
+3. Run three consecutive frozen-input vertical executions.
+4. Capture redacted latency, token, retry, repair, error-class, and cost summaries.
+5. Intentionally observe or safely simulate 429, timeout, malformed structured output, and thinking-only response behavior.
+6. Run live OpenAlex, arXiv, Crossref, and DataCite smoke.
+
+### Acceptance
+
+- Three consecutive vertical runs complete under fixed budgets.
+- No credential or prompt body appears in logs or artifacts.
+- Retry/repair counts remain bounded and attributable.
+- Cost is calculable or the run fails closed.
+- Provider behavior is reported for the exact model and date; it is not generalized to all models.
+
+## 15. Gate L — real scientific capability acceptance
+
+This gate is mandatory before claiming the system produces reliable research designs or scientific novelty.
+
+### Required evidence
+
+1. A frozen external holdout not used to design prompts, rules, or thresholds.
+2. Real primary-source records with DOI/PMID/repository commit and claim-level support checks.
+3. At least one executable baseline reproduction package with environment, data access, preprocessing, split, seeds, logs, and result digest.
+4. Controlled baseline, single-module, full, and interaction/leave-one-out experiments.
+5. Statistical uncertainty, robustness, compute, and failure analysis.
+6. Data availability, license, privacy, ethics, and human-subject approvals where applicable.
+7. Blinded domain-expert review with explicit rubric.
+8. Inter-rater agreement and adjudication of disagreements.
+9. Calibrated false-GO, false-NO_GO, unsupported-claim, citation-mismatch, and repair-success rates.
+10. A limitations statement that distinguishes local evidence from global novelty.
+
+### Acceptance
+
+- No critical claim is uncovered; unknown claims remain explicitly unknown.
+- Results represented as observed have immutable evidence.
+- Reproduction meets its predeclared tolerance.
+- Human reviewers meet the predeclared acceptance and agreement threshold.
+- Release decision is traceable to the frozen rubric and holdout, not post-hoc narrative.
+
